# General Modular Architecture Guidelines (WoW AddOns, Lua 11.x)

This document captures project-agnostic, reusable patterns we applied while refactoring. Use it as a living guide for future work across features and locales.

## Core Principles

1) Single responsibility: Each module owns one area (e.g., Gossip, Tracker, UI, Details, Utils, RTL).
2) Clear boundaries: Keep logic isolated; expose a minimal API per module via a common namespace.
3) Namespacing, not globals: Use the WoW namespacing pattern and avoid leaking globals.
4) Backward compatibility: Provide thin global wrappers that delegate to the new module APIs.
5) Explicit dependencies: Load modules in deterministic order via `.toc` and keep runtime checks defensive.
6) Idempotent hooks: Hook once; ensure repeated calls are safe and side‑effect free.
7) Null‑safety everywhere: Frames may be nil or not yet visible; guard all UI access.
8) Performance: Localize hot global lookups, avoid heavy work in tight loops, and throttle updates.
9) Configurable, not hardcoded: Abstract special cases (e.g., RTL) behind helpers; no scattered `lang == 'AR'` checks.

## Recommended Structure

Top‑level example (adapt paths per addon):

```
common/
  RTL.lua                # RTL / directionality helpers
  Quests/
    Utils.lua            # Pure helpers (fonts, layout, formatting)
    Gossip.lua           # Gossip toggle logic (GossipFrame / QuestFrame greeting)
    Main.lua             # Init, buttons/hooks, save, get quest id, toggle entrypoint
    Tracker.lua          # Objective tracker category titles + list updates
    UI.lua               # Quest UI helpers (map details, click handlers, next objective)
    Details.lua          # TranslateOn/Off, QuestPrepare, display constants
Plugins/                 # Optional integration shims (Immersion, Storyline, DUI, etc.)
Libs/                    # Third‑party libs (LibStub, Ace*, LDB, etc.)
Locales/                 # Localized data, quest/gossip payloads per language
```

Loading order (via `.toc`), after core and libs:

1) `RTL.lua`
2) `Quests/Utils.lua`
3) `Quests/Gossip.lua`
4) `Quests/Main.lua`
5) `Quests/Tracker.lua`
6) `Quests/UI.lua`
7) `Quests/Details.lua`

Rationale: Utils first (pure helpers), then feature modules; Details last since it can depend on Utils and other data.

## Namespacing Pattern

Use the standard WoW pattern to prevent global collisions and share a single namespace across files:

```lua
local addonName, ns = ...
ns = ns or {}
ns.Quests = ns.Quests or {}
-- Define submodules under ns.Quests.*
```

Expose functions as module methods (e.g., `ns.Quests.Details.TranslateOn`) and keep global wrappers only for back‑compat.

## Wrapper vs. Implementation

- Implementation lives inside `ns.*` modules.
- Thin wrappers keep legacy global function names and immediately delegate, e.g.:

```lua
function QTR_Translate_On(typ, event)
  if ns and ns.Quests and ns.Quests.Details and ns.Quests.Details.TranslateOn then
    return ns.Quests.Details.TranslateOn(typ, event)
  end
end
```

Guideline: wrappers do not duplicate logic. They only route calls to the new module API.

## RTL / Directionality

Isolate all directionality logic in `RTL.lua` so UI code stays clean and language‑agnostic.

- `RTL.IsRTL()`: single truth for directionality.
- `RTL.JustifyFontString(fontString, defaultJustify)`: use for alignment.
- `RTL.ApplyOptionButtonLayout(button)`: positions icon/text for RTL vs LTR.

Never scatter `lang == 'AR'` across feature modules — call the RTL helpers instead.

## UI + ScrollBox Patterns

- Use ScrollBox pools’ `ProcessActiveObjects` or enumerators; avoid stale references.
- After `SetText/SetFont`, re‑measure and optionally `Resize()`.
- For buttons with icons, compute text padding from icon width; don’t hardcode offsets.
- Do not assume regions exist — detect first FontString via a helper and guard nils.

## Hooks & Events

- Hook once per frame/function; idempotent lambdas preferred.
- Prefer WoW API hooks like `hooksecurefunc` over overwriting.
- Delay dependent work until frames are visible (e.g., via `C_Timer.After` or a safe wait helper).

## Performance & Safety

- Localize hot globals: `local strsub, gsub = string.sub, string.gsub`, etc.
- Avoid string concatenation in tight loops; precompute where possible.
- Batch updates when possible (e.g., compute, then apply once to the frame).
- Guard every UI access: the frame or region may be nil or not yet created.

## Data & SavedVariables

- Initialize saved variables once with defaults.
- Treat saved data as untrusted (nil‑check, type‑check) before use.

## Compatibility & API Stability

- Keep global function names via thin wrappers for third‑party compatibility.
- Additive changes: prefer adding new module APIs over breaking old ones.
- Version detection: use `GetBuildInfo()` or feature detection before using new APIs.

## Code Style & Conventions

- Module files define public functions on `ns.<Feature>.*`.
- Use descriptive names: `TranslateOn`, `QuestPrepare`, `ObjectiveTrackerFrame_Titles`.
- Keep function bodies focused; large chunks split across files (`UI`, `Tracker`, `Details`).
- Use consistent justification behavior via RTL helpers.

## Migration Strategy (Refactors)

1) Create new module and implement the logic there.
2) Add wrapper(s) that immediately delegate to the module.
3) Update `.toc` ordering to load the module before wrappers are called.
4) Keep wrappers for back‑compat; remove legacy bodies when safe.
5) Extract special‑case logic (e.g., RTL, Utils) into dedicated helpers.

## Example: Gossip Toggle (Pattern)

```lua
-- Quests/Gossip.lua
function ns.Quests.Gossip.ToggleNPCGossip()
  local isRTL = ns.RTL and ns.RTL.IsRTL and ns.RTL.IsRTL() or false
  -- 1) Apply greeting text based on isRTL
  -- 2) Set option buttons via Utils.ApplyOptionButtonLayout(button, isRTL)
end

-- Legacy wrapper (compat)
function GS_ON_OFF()
  return ns.Quests.Gossip.ToggleNPCGossip()
end
```

## Checklist Before Shipping

- [ ] Wrappers delegate to modules; no duplicate logic
- [ ] `.toc` load order valid for all locales/addons
- [ ] All directionality via `ns.RTL.*` helpers
- [ ] Defensive nil‑checks on frames and regions
- [ ] Hooks idempotent; no double work
- [ ] Saved variables initialized with defaults
- [ ] No new global leaks
- [ ] Verified on newest build (11.x) with feature detection where needed

